Now I can see the issue. The ISO date format uses the standard parsing mechanism, but when delegating to Java (in JVM) or JSJoda (in commonJs), they don't support excessive leading zeroes. 

Let me first understand the actual problem by implementing the second bug fix (the "P" issue) in DateTimePeriod parsing, and then work on the first one.

Looking at the DateTimePeriod parsing logic, I can see that at line 264-266 in DateTimePeriod.kt, there's a check:

```kotlin
if (i >= text.length) {
    if (state == START)
        parseException("Unexpected end of input; 'P' designator is required", i)
    if (state == AFTER_T)
        parseException("Unexpected end of input; at least one time component is required after 'T'", i)
    // ... then it continues to return a valid DateTimePeriod
}
```

This means that if the string is just "P" (state = AFTER_P), it doesn't raise an error and instead proceeds to return `DateTimePeriod(0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0)`. According to ISO 8601, this should not be valid.

